                      <locus target="#54v" facs="058"/> A symbol in the margin marks the midpoint of the Psalms
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e3">
                    <desc>
                      <locus target="#116r" facs="119"> f. 116r, line 5</locus>: a line of text has lines drawn above and below to signal its erasure in order to correct a homoeoteleuton
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e4">
                    <desc>
                      <locus target="#71v" facs="075"/>: Scrawls with ink pen
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e5">
                      <desc>
                        The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line.
                        Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an
                        appropriate aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate
                        script size. But, where the line of text is still too long, the scribe
                        completes the line of text above the end of the line (throughout). This
                        scribe also will reduce the font size at the end of lines to avoid
                        having to go onto the next line (e.g., <locus target="#4v #5r #7r #10v" facs="008 010 014"/>).
                      </desc>
                    </item>

                    </list>
